70","1370–Female":"1370–Overleden","1320–Male":"1320–Overleden","1345":"1345","Abt 1365":"circa 1365","1320":"1320","1340":"1340","before 1370":"vóór 1370","Abt 1345":"circa 1345","1370":"1370","Copley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Copley, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Copley, Yorkshire, England":"Copley, Yorkshire, England","Gnosall, Stafford district, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Gnosall, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1345–before 1370":"about 1345–before 1370","1345–1370":"1345–1370","1340–1370":"1340–1370","1370–Female":"1370–Deceased","1320–Male":"1320–Deceased","1345":"1345","Abt 1365":"about 1365","1320":"1320","1340":"1340","before 1370":"before 1370","Abt 1345":"about 1345","1370":"1370","Copley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Copley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Copley, Yorkshire, England":"Copley, Yorkshire, England","Gnosall, Stafford district, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Gnosall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Keighley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place so named in Yorkshire. The placename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Cyhha</i> + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Americanized form of German <b>Kiechle</b> (see   Kuechle  ) or <b>Kiechler</b> (see   Kuechler  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Keithley","meanings":["English (Durham and Yorkshire): variant of   Keighley  ."]},{"name":"Kuechle","meanings":["South German (<b>Küchle</b>): metonymic occupational name for a pastry cook, from <i>Küchle</i> ‘cookie, little cake’ (see   Kuchler   1)."]},{"name":"Keathley","meanings":["English: variant of   Keighley  ."]},{"name":"Keightley","meanings":["English: variant of   Keighley  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gatlaoich</b>, see   Gately  ."]},{"name":"Keatley","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Keighley  ."]},{"name":"Keithly","meanings":["English: variant of   Keighley  ."]},{"name":"Keigley","meanings":["Altered form of English   Keighley  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"J